WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.940
So, I am really so thrilled to introduce our next keynote speakers, Martin Wattenberg and

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:23.480
Fernanda Viegas, because Martin and Fernanda, I believe, are really two of the top visualization

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:25.799
researchers in the world today.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:31.760
I have been a follower of their work for over 10 years, the chances are you have seen some

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:32.759
of their work before.

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:36.799
In fact, if you've ever looked up the definition of a word on Google and seen the little line

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:42.880
chart, I believe that is Martin's most popular or most well-seen visualization.

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:51.639
One of my personal favorites is a wind map, really beautiful visualization of dynamic wind

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:53.400
currents over the continental US.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:57.480
If you Google wind map, fantastic, fantastic visualization.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:03.439
But recently, Fernanda and Martin have been working on using visualization to display

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:09.000
really complex ideas and unpack many of the tools of modern machine learning and artificial

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:10.000
intelligence.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.879
So, please join me in welcoming Fernanda and Martin.

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:15.879
Thank you.

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:16.879
Thank you.

00:01:16.879 --> 00:01:17.879
Thank you.

00:01:21.879 --> 00:01:24.879
So, yeah, thank you so much.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:30.639
I want to talk a little bit about what we're doing now, because it combines both visualization,

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:35.599
which has been our bread and butter for a while, with AI.

00:01:35.599 --> 00:01:41.400
Our co-leads, with Jeff Holbrook, a group at Google called PAIR, stands for People Plus

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:43.279
AI Research.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:48.839
Before saying anything more about it, I want to quickly put up pictures of the people on

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:52.720
the team, because I want to emphasize that everything we're talking about today, this

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:59.320
was all very much a team effort, and these people deserve credit.

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:05.279
The sort of mission of PAIR is to make machine learning and artificial intelligence productive,

00:02:05.279 --> 00:02:07.680
enjoyable, and fair.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:09.240
We do that in various ways.

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:13.199
One of which I'm happy to say, actually, we've released a fair number of open source tools,

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:15.720
which we will talk about today.

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:21.199
We also create educational materials, academic publications, and do a lot of public work

00:02:21.199 --> 00:02:22.199
as well.

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:28.960
Now, you might ask, why are we talking about human-AI interaction at this conference?

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:33.679
And there's sort of a snarky answer you could give, which is that some might say AI is just

00:02:33.679 --> 00:02:38.279
fancy statistics, and maybe there's some truth to that.

00:02:38.279 --> 00:02:45.080
But there is kind of a more serious answer, which is that you, as people who analyze data,

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:47.199
you have a lot of power, and you know that.

00:02:47.199 --> 00:02:53.479
But you might have even more power than you realize, that as AI becomes more and more

00:02:53.479 --> 00:03:01.880
pervasive, it's turning out that data analysis is very much the key to getting AI right.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.320
So to start with, we're going to start at the beginning.

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:10.839
We have a few projects we'd like to share with you, and one of them is about just visualizing

00:03:10.839 --> 00:03:12.839
training data.

00:03:12.839 --> 00:03:19.199
I'm sure you all know this, that a big part of what goes into these massive machine learning

00:03:19.199 --> 00:03:26.119
systems is the data, and you need to be super careful and mindful about the data.

00:03:26.119 --> 00:03:31.759
And yet, when we talk with engineers, software engineers, about some of the problems that

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:38.559
come up in these systems, their first instinct tends to be to debug their program.

00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:43.240
And so our favorite motto is debug your data first, not your program.

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:45.639
And this is something of a learning curve.

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:52.880
And I think you all are way ahead of the engineers, but one of the realities is that we need tools

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:59.720
for dealing with the huge amounts of data that these people are using.

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:01.800
And so we're still working on that.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:08.639
One example of a tool we created, which is a visualization for just training data, I'm

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:14.880
going to demo that with one of the Hello World datasets of machine learning, which is called

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:16.399
CIFAR-10.

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:24.920
And all it is, it's a bunch of images, square little images of 10 different classes of things.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:30.200
Each image has just one main object or entity inside of it.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:35.559
And the entire dataset has been human labeled in these 10 different classes.

00:04:35.559 --> 00:04:41.279
So you have deer, you have car, you have automobile, and so forth.

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:47.760
And another thing that's important about this dataset is that because it is one of the Hello

00:04:47.760 --> 00:04:51.760
World datasets of machine learning, it is used everywhere.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:53.279
It is used as a benchmark.

00:04:53.279 --> 00:04:59.200
It's been used by thousands of people all over the world, and it's used in publications

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:00.200
as well.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.200
So how do I get...

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:08.519
Maybe that X?

00:05:08.519 --> 00:05:10.239
Let's get to the demo.

00:05:10.239 --> 00:05:11.239
Okay.

00:05:11.239 --> 00:05:12.239
Cool.

00:05:12.239 --> 00:05:17.200
So this is our little visualization, and it's called Facets.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:23.920
And all I'm doing here is visualizing the images I have just by the different classes.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:28.600
So as far as data visualization goes, it's extremely straightforward, right?

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:36.880
I can zoom in, I can look at images very closely if I want, see how pixelated they are, and

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:37.880
so forth.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:39.320
Nothing super special.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:44.079
You can see the labels of the classes, and you can also see that if I accidentally click

00:05:44.079 --> 00:05:49.799
on any one of the images, it brings up a little card at the very top there with the

00:05:49.799 --> 00:05:53.679
metadata about each one of these images.

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:54.679
Okay.

00:05:54.679 --> 00:05:57.559
So far, nothing special.

00:05:57.559 --> 00:06:04.600
But even this is hard for regular engineers using machine learning systems to get to see.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:07.359
They don't usually get to see their training data.

00:06:07.359 --> 00:06:12.440
And the reason why I'm sure you all realize why you want to do something like this is

00:06:12.799 --> 00:06:17.959
because it could be that half of your data set is just empty, it's just blank images.

00:06:17.959 --> 00:06:23.920
Or even worse than that, it could be that just one of your classes is blank and nothing

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:25.320
else.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:31.519
And so you want to be able to just very quickly play with your data and look at it.

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:34.000
Once we have this, we can play little games, right?

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.239
So I can look at the same visualization, but I can now distribute it by hue.

00:06:40.239 --> 00:06:44.720
And I can see that there are different bulges in different classes.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:50.440
So I can see that airplane at the very top and ship towards the bottom are the classes

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:54.600
with the most blue images, right?

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:55.959
That kind of makes sense.

00:06:55.959 --> 00:07:00.679
I'm taking images, I'm taking photos against the sky or against the water.

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:07.799
And then all of my animal classes, kind of in the middle, bird, cat, deer, they tend

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:10.839
to hang out more on the earthy tones.

00:07:10.839 --> 00:07:13.079
Okay, so far so good.

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:14.440
Now I can do other things.

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:19.040
I can say, now show me a confusion matrix.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:26.880
And all it is, a confusion matrix is basically me trying to understand how in sync humans

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:30.200
and my machine learning system really are.

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:36.440
So everything on the column there are the labels that have been manually given to these

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:38.119
images by humans.

00:07:38.119 --> 00:07:44.079
And everything at the top are the labels that my system is giving as it tries to classify

00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:45.600
these images.

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:52.160
So the good news for me is that that diagonal is by far the most populated set of cells

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:56.160
I have there, because that's where humans and machine agree.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:58.079
So that's great.

00:07:58.079 --> 00:08:03.399
But then other things I can do with this, I can say, okay, so now let's filter out all

00:08:03.399 --> 00:08:04.399
the correct guesses.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.839
I'm going to filter out that diagonal.

00:08:08.839 --> 00:08:12.880
And then immediately I have all the mistakes that my system is making.

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:15.959
And I can see an interesting pattern here.

00:08:15.959 --> 00:08:25.679
I can see that my most populated cell or couple of cells over here and over here is the intersection

00:08:25.679 --> 00:08:27.480
between cats and dogs.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:31.920
My system is kind of confused between cats and dogs, right?

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:38.440
So it could be that at this point I go back and give my system more examples of cats and

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:43.679
dogs so we can retrain and hopefully get better at these classes.

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:45.960
This could be one of the things I do.

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.080
All right.

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:52.599
Another thing I can do with this visualization is look at the softmax labels.

00:08:52.599 --> 00:09:00.760
So towards the end of my network, I want to understand not only how these images are being

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:08.599
classified by my system, but I also want to understand how sure my system is, how certain my

00:09:08.599 --> 00:09:13.960
system is of any of those classifications it makes.

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:22.760
So the way to read this is the more an image is to the right, the more certain my system is that

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:27.200
that is indeed a dog or a cat or an airplane.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:33.799
And everything, the more to the right, the more correct it is.

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:42.559
On the contrary, the more to the left you have these over here, the more certain my system is that that is

00:09:42.559 --> 00:09:45.799
not a cat or not an airplane.

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:49.960
And those are incorrect classifications.

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:56.200
So one of the things I might want to do here is I might want to go, we became interested.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:58.280
We're like, oh, wow, but check it out.

00:09:58.280 --> 00:10:00.679
Cats is still very populated here.

00:10:00.679 --> 00:10:02.000
There's a bunch of cats.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.320
My system is very, very sure are not cats.

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:12.200
So we zoomed in and started looking like, wow, what do these cats look like that my system just very

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:15.320
certain aren't cats, right?

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:26.159
And again, think back that this is a benchmark dataset used by lots of people all over the world.

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:33.960
We started looking at this and we're like, there is totally a thing there that's not a cat.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:40.520
Can you, can anyone spot it's towards, it's on the second row to the bottom.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:51.359
Over here, my system is very sure that's a frog and so am I.

00:10:51.359 --> 00:10:57.479
And yet it has been labeled by humans as a cat.

00:10:57.479 --> 00:10:58.520
Okay.

00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:02.159
So what is our little tale telling us here?

00:11:02.159 --> 00:11:03.719
The same tale as usual.

00:11:03.719 --> 00:11:06.200
You have to go back to your data and look at it.

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:08.200
And there are going to be mistakes.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:16.679
And if you can't look at it in an easy way, you're going to continue to see these mistakes over and over again.

00:11:16.679 --> 00:11:25.719
So this was a tool that we started using internally and then decided this is actually a simple,

00:11:25.719 --> 00:11:29.760
straightforward tool that's actually super useful.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.479
And we decided to open source.

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:38.080
So facets is a open source tool available for anyone.

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:43.520
And yes, I know that you can do this in R.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:47.200
And I'm sure that a lot of you are doing it already, right?

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:51.159
Slice and dicing, simple, simple stuff.

00:11:51.159 --> 00:11:53.719
But there's a lot of people who don't use R too.

00:11:53.719 --> 00:12:00.840
And so having something on the web is also useful.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:01.400
All right.

00:12:01.400 --> 00:12:10.960
The next thing we want to talk about is this notion that as soon as you start feeding these massive data sets to these machine learning systems,

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:16.719
you are going to be talking about bias and skews in your data set.

00:12:16.719 --> 00:12:26.080
And as soon as you start deploying these systems in the world, you are going to be faced with fairness questions.

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:31.640
And so one of the things, and these are very complicated, these are very complex issues, right?

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:37.119
It's not like you have a technical solution for these things.

00:12:37.119 --> 00:12:41.840
But there is also a technical piece to trying to solve some of these things.

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:57.200
So Martin and I were interested in whether we could use very simple data visualization to start illustrating some of the trade-offs that you have to make when you start thinking about fairness in machine learning.

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:02.520
And so we're going to play, as I introduce this visualization, it's very simple.

00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:16.080
We're going to play a little game here, which is we're going to imagine that we are a bank and we're deciding who we're going to give loans to and who we're going to not give loans to.

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:23.159
So each one of these dots is a person who comes to our bank asking for a loan.

00:13:23.159 --> 00:13:23.880
OK.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:26.599
They have a credit score.

00:13:26.599 --> 00:13:28.359
All of these things are imaginary.

00:13:28.359 --> 00:13:32.359
My credit score goes from 0 to 100.

00:13:32.359 --> 00:13:39.400
And their location reflects their credit score.

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:41.640
OK.

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:51.359
Each one of the light colored dots would default on our loan.

00:13:51.359 --> 00:13:54.440
All of the dark colored dots would pay us back.

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:58.000
So in other words, we want to give loans to the dark colored dots

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.119
and we do not want to give loans to the light colored dots.

00:14:01.119 --> 00:14:01.880
OK.

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:04.640
Many people come to our bank.

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:06.400
We set a threshold.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.919
Below that threshold, we don't give loans.

00:14:08.919 --> 00:14:11.440
Above that threshold, we give loans.

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:12.960
So far, so good.

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:18.080
Except that in reality, life is not that simple, right?

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:25.880
So no matter where I put my threshold, chances are I'm going to be denying loans to people who would pay me back.

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:30.320
And I would be giving loans to people who default.

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:34.760
And so this is still a simplification of the real world,

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:39.919
but it's a distribution that starts to look a little bit more realistic.

00:14:39.919 --> 00:14:42.719
And you can see that no matter where you put your threshold,

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:46.359
you're going to make incorrect guesses, right?

00:14:46.359 --> 00:14:47.880
OK.

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:53.080
Then the next question becomes, well, you

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:59.960
may have different populations of people coming to your bank and asking for loans.

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:04.880
And you may know that these distributions are different for these different people.

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:09.159
And so how are you going to be fair in deciding,

00:15:09.159 --> 00:15:14.760
now that you have a blue population and an orange population with different distributions,

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:19.599
how are you going to decide how to be fair?

00:15:19.599 --> 00:15:22.679
And there are many different ways you can do this.

00:15:22.679 --> 00:15:31.039
So let me just show you the little demo slash visualization we created.

00:15:31.039 --> 00:15:38.080
This accompanies, by the way, a paper on machine learning fairness.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:42.679
So basically, we just created this little simulation here,

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:46.280
which is kind of what you had been seeing before.

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:49.200
And it's interactive, and I can play with it.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:50.599
And you can see what happens.

00:15:51.039 --> 00:15:55.760
As I am changing the threshold here at the top, at the bottom,

00:15:55.760 --> 00:16:02.960
you can see the percentage of incorrect and correct guesses I make, OK?

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:08.000
You can also see things at the bottom here, these pie chart things.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:14.799
They stand for the positive rate of loans I give.

00:16:14.799 --> 00:16:18.080
So in other words, of all the people who come to my bank,

00:16:18.119 --> 00:16:21.359
what is the percentage of people I give loans to?

00:16:21.359 --> 00:16:28.159
And then there's another pie chart that says, sorry, the positive rate is on the right.

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:30.320
True positive rate is on the left.

00:16:30.320 --> 00:16:36.919
True positive rate means of all the people who come to my bank and would pay me back,

00:16:36.919 --> 00:16:41.000
what is the percentage of people I give loans to?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.599
So I can play with this stuff.

00:16:42.599 --> 00:16:44.520
I can play with them independently.

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:47.960
And the other thing I want to make sure, because I'm a bank,

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:51.359
is I want to make a profit at the end of the day.

00:16:51.359 --> 00:16:53.440
So how do I do these things?

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:55.599
And still, how can I be fair?

00:16:55.599 --> 00:16:59.239
So we put some presets here on the left.

00:16:59.239 --> 00:17:04.000
One is if you don't want to be fair at all, click on maximum profit.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:04.920
There it is.

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:08.079
That's what your thresholds should be given the distributions.

00:17:08.079 --> 00:17:09.160
OK.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:11.880
If you do want to be fair, all right.

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:15.959
Maybe what you want to do is you want to be group unaware.

00:17:15.959 --> 00:17:17.640
So I clicked on group unaware.

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:23.280
And you can see that what this means is I have the same thresholds for both populations.

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:23.800
Right.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:25.640
So I don't care if you're blue.

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:27.400
I don't care if you're orange.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:31.400
You're going to be treated the same because that's the most fair thing to do.

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:33.400
That's the fair thing to do.

00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:35.160
OK.

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:36.680
That could be.

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:41.800
Except that when we start looking at the positive rates here,

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:47.239
I can see that of all the people who pay me back, the blue people,

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:54.959
I give loans to 81% of them versus only 60% of the orange people.

00:17:54.959 --> 00:17:57.239
OK.

00:17:57.239 --> 00:17:58.560
Is that fair?

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:04.400
Well, maybe the next thing you could try is something called demographic parity.

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:09.119
And demographic parity optimizes for the same positive rate.

00:18:09.119 --> 00:18:14.319
So of all the blue and all the orange people who come to my bank,

00:18:14.319 --> 00:18:19.560
I try to give the same percentage of loans.

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:23.599
Again, what this means is my thresholds are different, quite different

00:18:23.599 --> 00:18:26.160
for these different groups.

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:26.839
Is that fair?

00:18:26.839 --> 00:18:27.359
Maybe.

00:18:27.359 --> 00:18:28.280
Maybe not.

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:30.839
Then that last thing here I have is equal opportunity,

00:18:30.839 --> 00:18:33.400
which optimizes for a true positive rate.

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:39.040
Anyway, long story short, there are many different ways

00:18:39.040 --> 00:18:42.160
to think about being fair.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:45.920
And how do you translate those values into math

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:49.599
for deciding in a scenario like this?

00:18:49.599 --> 00:18:54.800
The point of doing this was that Martin and I were interested

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:59.560
if with a very simple abstract scenario like this,

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:02.800
with a simple visualization that people could just play with,

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:07.439
if they could start to develop a certain intuition for the trade-offs

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:12.199
that happen when you're actually trying to decide this on a system.

00:19:12.199 --> 00:19:16.479
And it was interesting to see that this simple visualization

00:19:16.479 --> 00:19:18.560
went kind of viral on the web.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:23.479
And we started seeing people have these really interesting discussions of,

00:19:23.479 --> 00:19:26.920
oh, wow, I always thought that demographic parity was the way to go.

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:30.520
But now I see that whatever, equal opportunity

00:19:30.520 --> 00:19:34.479
is maybe a more interesting way to think about fair.

00:19:34.479 --> 00:19:39.959
And just to be clear, there are many, many more metrics of fairness

00:19:39.959 --> 00:19:45.839
that have come up since then also in the literature.

00:19:45.839 --> 00:19:49.959
And I think that's not going to stop.

00:19:49.959 --> 00:19:52.599
Another part of the conversation that we saw online

00:19:52.599 --> 00:19:58.199
that is, I think, very important is people realizing, oh,

00:19:58.199 --> 00:20:01.920
and you can't have all of these at once.

00:20:01.920 --> 00:20:04.640
There is no perfect solution, right?

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:08.880
It's always a trade-off, and you're going to have to choose.

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:10.719
And so we started getting emails.

00:20:10.719 --> 00:20:13.560
And so for instance, one of the emails we got

00:20:13.560 --> 00:20:19.520
was from a criminal justice department in the US saying,

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:21.239
we saw this visualization.

00:20:21.239 --> 00:20:27.839
Do you think we could create something like this for our own department

00:20:27.839 --> 00:20:30.800
so that we start to understand what the trade-offs are

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:34.119
that we're making with the systems we're using?

00:20:34.119 --> 00:20:36.119
Obviously, we're not a bank.

00:20:36.119 --> 00:20:43.199
But this would be a very powerful way to have people in the department

00:20:43.199 --> 00:20:45.920
engage with these questions, right?

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:56.239
And so based on this and on the reaction we got, let me go back,

00:20:56.239 --> 00:20:58.959
we decided to go from that toy simulation

00:20:58.959 --> 00:21:02.319
to actually trying to put together an actual tool that

00:21:02.319 --> 00:21:07.479
allowed you to do some of this playing around with your model

00:21:07.479 --> 00:21:12.199
and with testing your model for different scenarios.

00:21:12.199 --> 00:21:16.400
And so this is a tool we created called the What-If Tool.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:22.760
And this is a code-free probing tool for machine learning systems

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:27.479
that allows you to test for some of these scenarios,

00:21:27.479 --> 00:21:32.000
to say things like, oh, what if I want demographic parity

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.800
in the different slices of my data?

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:38.599
What thresholds should I use in my model?

00:21:38.599 --> 00:21:43.719
It allows you to do things like click on a data point and say,

00:21:43.719 --> 00:21:47.160
for instance, let's go back to the loan scenario and say,

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:51.599
oh, this person did not get a loan, OK?

00:21:51.599 --> 00:21:55.000
Let me go back to the next slide here.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.040
This person did not get a loan.

00:21:58.040 --> 00:22:02.760
Who is the nearest person to that one that did get a loan?

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:04.839
And what is the delta there?

00:22:04.839 --> 00:22:08.760
So a little notion of counterfactual, if you will,

00:22:08.760 --> 00:22:10.000
without the causality.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:11.920
That's a separate conversation.

00:22:11.920 --> 00:22:15.359
But just this notion of starting to try to understand

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:18.680
what's happening with these systems, how they are behaving,

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:21.640
asking a bunch of alternative scenarios,

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:25.319
trying a bunch of edge cases, and also

00:22:25.319 --> 00:22:28.040
playing with notions of fairness,

00:22:28.040 --> 00:22:31.479
of how different slices of your data set

00:22:31.479 --> 00:22:36.239
are doing vis-a-vis one another.

00:22:36.239 --> 00:22:41.239
This tool is open source, so it is available for anyone.

00:22:41.239 --> 00:22:45.760
It has also been integrated into Google's Cloud AI

00:22:45.760 --> 00:22:49.079
so that anyone using that platform

00:22:49.079 --> 00:22:52.079
can now play with these alternative scenarios

00:22:52.079 --> 00:22:55.199
and test things for themselves before they decide

00:22:55.199 --> 00:22:59.920
to launch something or to try to debug situations.

00:22:59.920 --> 00:23:02.359
And I think one of the really important things here, too,

00:23:02.359 --> 00:23:04.479
is the fact that we're not expecting

00:23:04.479 --> 00:23:08.800
that you need to be a PhD in machine learning

00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:11.920
to ask these probing questions.

00:23:11.959 --> 00:23:17.959
Many more people should be engaging and experimenting

00:23:17.959 --> 00:23:21.880
with the way these systems behave.

00:23:21.880 --> 00:23:24.319
So I think the story so far is that you're

00:23:24.319 --> 00:23:28.160
seeing how important data analysis is in all of this.

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:30.800
And then I think also, when you look at machine learning

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:33.400
fairness, there's this issue, number one,

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:35.640
that trying to make the world better,

00:23:35.640 --> 00:23:38.560
to try to do the right thing, involves statistics.

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:41.040
However, also, if you are deploying models,

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:42.920
this is something you now have to think about

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:46.359
or should have been thinking about all along, indeed.

00:23:46.359 --> 00:23:49.040
And I think that's an important change of mindset

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:50.400
for many people that we've seen.

00:23:50.400 --> 00:23:53.359
And again, statistics is a key part of this.

00:23:53.359 --> 00:23:55.040
There's something else going on, though,

00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:57.400
which is that using data analysis,

00:23:57.400 --> 00:24:01.839
you can actually end up finding new ways to control AI systems.

00:24:01.839 --> 00:24:04.479
And to explain that, we're going to take a journey

00:24:04.479 --> 00:24:10.160
through high-dimensional space to understand the superpower.

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:12.800
So let's talk about data in high dimensions.

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:16.680
And we're going to introduce a couple of things in a row here.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:18.199
We'll start with a warm-up.

00:24:18.199 --> 00:24:20.959
And for our warm-up, we're going to visualize

00:24:20.959 --> 00:24:24.920
another famous Hello World data set for machine learning,

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:27.760
a data set of little 28 by 28 icons

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:30.280
that represent handwritten digits that

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:34.040
is often used to test very simple machine learning models.

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:35.479
And what we're going to talk about

00:24:35.479 --> 00:24:38.119
is how you can think about each of these images

00:24:38.119 --> 00:24:40.439
as a vector in high-dimensional space.

00:24:40.439 --> 00:24:42.800
And the trick, which is familiar, I'm sure,

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:47.479
to some, if not many of you, is that we look at the pixels

00:24:47.479 --> 00:24:49.000
and we give them all values.

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:52.079
In this case, we'll say black is 0, white is 1,

00:24:52.079 --> 00:24:55.000
and intermediate values get some floating point number.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.280
And then we just list the values of all the pixels in a row.

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:01.359
And that gives us a vector.

00:25:01.359 --> 00:25:03.599
So for example, this vector would turn into something

00:25:03.599 --> 00:25:05.680
that looks like that.

00:25:06.359 --> 00:25:10.839
Other images would turn into other vectors.

00:25:10.839 --> 00:25:12.719
OK, so why have we done this?

00:25:12.719 --> 00:25:15.199
Well, this is going to be sort of our example data

00:25:15.199 --> 00:25:18.119
set as we look at a visualization that we

00:25:18.119 --> 00:25:20.079
call the embedding projector.

00:25:20.079 --> 00:25:23.839
So let's take a look.

00:25:23.839 --> 00:25:27.439
All right, yes, so now you see rotating.

00:25:27.439 --> 00:25:32.079
You are looking at 784-dimensional space here.

00:25:32.079 --> 00:25:34.479
What you are actually seeing, of course,

00:25:34.479 --> 00:25:38.359
is a two-dimensional projection of a three-dimensional view

00:25:38.359 --> 00:25:40.520
of this high-dimensional space that

00:25:40.520 --> 00:25:42.359
is using principal component analysis

00:25:42.359 --> 00:25:44.920
to project these linearly.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:47.000
And that's definitely an interesting thing.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:51.239
But it also is kind of a big blob.

00:25:51.239 --> 00:25:53.920
As much as one can ooh and aah over this,

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:57.199
it's a little bit hard to make sense of.

00:25:57.199 --> 00:26:00.400
So let's take another view.

00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:05.599
Let's look at a different way of looking at this.

00:26:05.599 --> 00:26:08.119
OK, now we're using a method called

00:26:08.119 --> 00:26:14.839
UMAP that is designed to take high-dimensional space.

00:26:14.839 --> 00:26:17.520
And instead of using a linear projection,

00:26:17.520 --> 00:26:19.839
it's using a non-linear projection

00:26:19.839 --> 00:26:22.800
that has many complicated properties, which

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:24.000
we'll talk about in a moment.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.839
But the basic idea is that one thing it does tend to preserve

00:26:27.839 --> 00:26:29.359
is clustering.

00:26:29.359 --> 00:26:34.599
And so one thing that I can do is, since this is our data set

00:26:34.599 --> 00:26:38.199
and we have labels, I can label, I

00:26:38.199 --> 00:26:41.880
can color these digits by their label.

00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:44.359
And that lets us easily see, for example,

00:26:44.359 --> 00:26:47.839
that in general, all the 1's are in a certain area,

00:26:47.839 --> 00:26:49.800
all the 4's are in another area, and so forth.

00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:52.160
But we can also see it doesn't completely get it right.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:53.920
Like it thinks this 3 it clearly thinks

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:58.119
belongs with the 2's, this 8 looks like a 2, and so forth.

00:26:58.119 --> 00:27:01.400
Already, I think this view can tell you

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:04.280
a bunch of interesting things.

00:27:04.280 --> 00:27:08.040
One thing is just that apparently these digits are

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:09.359
actually pretty well-separated.

00:27:09.359 --> 00:27:12.280
Like you can see why this is not the hardest machine learning

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:14.239
task in the world, that there is just

00:27:14.239 --> 00:27:18.319
a natural clustering structure that is, you know,

00:27:18.319 --> 00:27:21.180
even a visualization method brings it out pretty well.

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:22.839
One other thing that's kind of nice,

00:27:22.839 --> 00:27:26.420
though, is that if you look even within these clusters,

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:28.459
you can start to see some interesting structure.

00:27:28.459 --> 00:27:30.339
For example, in these 1's, you'll

00:27:30.339 --> 00:27:33.540
notice that they're kind of tilted to the left on this side,

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:35.939
they're tilted to the right on this side,

00:27:35.939 --> 00:27:39.219
and you really can start to get a sense of what

00:27:39.219 --> 00:27:42.420
the geometry looks like in this high-dimensional space.

00:27:45.260 --> 00:27:47.819
OK, so let's see.

00:27:47.819 --> 00:27:48.900
I'll go back there.

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:55.540
What else can we do with high-dimensional space?

00:27:55.540 --> 00:27:58.140
Well, let's see.

00:27:58.140 --> 00:28:00.140
I think if there's time at the end,

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:02.900
we might talk a little bit about what these mean,

00:28:02.900 --> 00:28:05.140
but I think I might skip this.

00:28:05.140 --> 00:28:07.260
I will say that among the educational materials

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:10.699
that we've been putting out are sort of step-by-step

00:28:10.699 --> 00:28:13.260
interactive essays about how to interpret

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:15.300
these complicated nonlinear projections,

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:17.979
because they're amazing, but weird.

00:28:17.979 --> 00:28:20.859
And the weirdness can be your friend, but you have to have

00:28:20.859 --> 00:28:22.619
And sometimes problematic, so you

00:28:22.619 --> 00:28:25.900
have to be aware of that.

00:28:25.900 --> 00:28:30.619
OK, so another kind of high-dimensional object

00:28:30.619 --> 00:28:32.819
which turns out to be very, very useful

00:28:32.819 --> 00:28:34.619
is something called a word embedding.

00:28:34.619 --> 00:28:37.780
So word embedding, it's sort of a weird terminology,

00:28:37.780 --> 00:28:39.979
but what it just means is you're mapping words

00:28:39.979 --> 00:28:42.540
into points in high-dimensional space, much the way

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:44.819
we mapped those images.

00:28:44.819 --> 00:28:47.339
However, with images, there was a pretty straightforward way

00:28:47.339 --> 00:28:50.540
of doing it by using pixels.

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:52.540
With words, it's actually sort of complicated,

00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:54.619
and I won't get into exactly how that is done.

00:28:54.619 --> 00:28:55.739
There are actually a couple of ways,

00:28:55.739 --> 00:28:57.359
and the interesting thing is they often

00:28:57.359 --> 00:28:59.859
produce similar results if you do it well.

00:28:59.859 --> 00:29:03.260
The idea is usually to make sure that related words end up

00:29:03.260 --> 00:29:04.660
near each other.

00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:08.099
And in fact, it turns out you can do this.

00:29:08.099 --> 00:29:11.660
However, when people figured out ways to make that happen,

00:29:11.660 --> 00:29:14.260
they discovered a really interesting and surprising

00:29:14.260 --> 00:29:17.939
fact, which is not only can you get a situation where

00:29:17.939 --> 00:29:19.739
similar words are near each other,

00:29:19.739 --> 00:29:24.420
but almost as a byproduct, like seemingly as an accident,

00:29:24.420 --> 00:29:27.099
you get meaningful directions in space.

00:29:27.099 --> 00:29:28.780
And so the image that you're seeing here

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:32.939
is a figure from one very famous early paper in which they

00:29:32.939 --> 00:29:35.859
showed that there is a direction in space that

00:29:35.859 --> 00:29:39.060
corresponds to the relationship of a capital

00:29:39.060 --> 00:29:43.699
to the country it is a capital of, which is really amazing.

00:29:43.699 --> 00:29:46.619
OK, so let's take a look, just because we

00:29:46.619 --> 00:29:51.300
cover a visualization up, of what those word embeddings look

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:51.900
like.

00:29:51.900 --> 00:29:53.900
And I'm going to show this in a couple of ways.

00:29:53.900 --> 00:30:01.020
So this is just a raw PCA view.

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:10.500
This is a UMAP view.

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:13.380
And let's actually play with this a little bit.

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:15.800
Let us explore this, because I think

00:30:15.800 --> 00:30:17.640
it really gives a sense of you're

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:19.199
seeing the English language here.

00:30:19.199 --> 00:30:21.319
This is the geometry of English.

00:30:21.319 --> 00:30:22.680
And what can we say about it?

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:24.280
Well, there's obviously clumps.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:26.280
Let's go spelunking a little bit.

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:27.319
What is this clump here?

00:30:27.319 --> 00:30:29.520
Oh, look, a bunch of names.

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:32.479
Seems like largely maybe boys' names here.

00:30:32.479 --> 00:30:35.479
And then, let's see, we get some other names.

00:30:35.479 --> 00:30:36.359
It's hard for people.

00:30:36.359 --> 00:30:37.239
Yeah, I'll read them.

00:30:37.239 --> 00:30:40.800
Lloyd, Alex, Matt, Joel.

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:44.160
What about this cluster here?

00:30:44.160 --> 00:30:48.520
Horns, percussion, guitar, quartet, bass.

00:30:48.520 --> 00:30:50.839
We found the music cluster over there.

00:30:50.839 --> 00:30:51.560
What about these?

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:53.280
Oh, look, we have some numbers.

00:30:53.280 --> 00:30:56.119
And whoops, let's see if we can zoom in on them.

00:30:56.119 --> 00:30:58.479
0, 1, 2, 3.

00:30:58.479 --> 00:30:59.439
We can actually see it.

00:30:59.439 --> 00:31:00.819
In fact, if we zoomed in more, we

00:31:00.819 --> 00:31:03.479
can almost see a little bit of a linear structure

00:31:03.479 --> 00:31:04.760
representing those.

00:31:04.760 --> 00:31:06.880
We have some other things here.

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:09.280
Let's see, infinity, angle, math, BF.

00:31:09.280 --> 00:31:12.800
Look, we found the tech world here.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:14.479
So there really is everything.

00:31:14.479 --> 00:31:18.160
And this gives you a sense of just how much information

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:20.599
this is encoded here.

00:31:20.599 --> 00:31:24.439
But now I want to show one more thing.

00:31:24.439 --> 00:31:31.839
And that is, let's do something tricky.

00:31:31.839 --> 00:31:35.760
Let's go back to, let's do a custom embedding.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:38.900
And the way this works is we actually

00:31:38.900 --> 00:31:44.979
can define an axis in terms of one word to another word.

00:31:44.979 --> 00:31:47.180
Right now, it's just a 2D projection.

00:31:47.180 --> 00:31:47.819
It's linear.

00:31:47.819 --> 00:31:50.819
And both axes are random.

00:31:50.819 --> 00:31:53.619
But let's actually search for a word

00:31:53.619 --> 00:31:55.339
and look at some neighbors.

00:31:55.339 --> 00:31:56.900
Let's see, what's a good one?

00:31:56.900 --> 00:31:58.300
How about science?

00:32:02.420 --> 00:32:03.579
Click on this.

00:32:03.579 --> 00:32:06.140
We'll isolate those 100 points.

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:08.219
And now we can sort of see the neighbors

00:32:08.219 --> 00:32:10.939
of the word science in PCA.

00:32:10.939 --> 00:32:13.619
But now let's actually do a custom thing.

00:32:13.619 --> 00:32:18.180
And we can play this little game where, say, we look at,

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:24.300
let's look at man on the left and woman on the right.

00:32:24.300 --> 00:32:28.099
And suddenly, we see something really interesting,

00:32:28.099 --> 00:32:31.780
that now the left-to-right, that x-axis, left-to-right,

00:32:31.780 --> 00:32:33.339
has things that it's thinking are

00:32:33.339 --> 00:32:36.780
closer to the word man versus woman.

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:38.780
And this is actually a little bit sad,

00:32:38.780 --> 00:32:40.660
that you can sort of see, like, technical

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:44.780
is its most male word here in this neighborhood.

00:32:44.780 --> 00:32:47.900
And meanwhile, on the female side,

00:32:47.900 --> 00:32:51.420
although we do have scientists, we see religion, author,

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:53.219
stories, psychology.

00:32:53.219 --> 00:32:55.000
And this is actually a sobering moment.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.780
When people started to realize this about these embeddings,

00:32:57.780 --> 00:33:00.199
I think they just realized how serious things had become,

00:33:00.359 --> 00:33:02.359
that these things had been trained

00:33:02.359 --> 00:33:06.040
on a huge corpora of existing words and language.

00:33:06.040 --> 00:33:09.560
And those had contained a bunch of biases.

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:14.000
And this new word embedding was very efficiently

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.800
encoding some of those.

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:21.239
So in fact, we can show a couple of other examples.

00:33:21.239 --> 00:33:23.239
This is the neighborhood of engineer,

00:33:23.239 --> 00:33:26.239
shows many of the similar things.

00:33:26.239 --> 00:33:28.319
If you do a neighborhood of math.

00:33:28.319 --> 00:33:29.439
I want to read it out loud.

00:33:29.439 --> 00:33:33.239
Yeah, you can see geometry, computational on the man side.

00:33:33.239 --> 00:33:38.239
Again, psychology, art, library on the woman's side.

00:33:38.239 --> 00:33:43.640
And it's not even just sort of the big famous biases,

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:44.760
like gender or something.

00:33:44.760 --> 00:33:48.839
But even something like old and new, and not with people,

00:33:48.839 --> 00:33:51.319
you can sort of see interesting things that are meaningful.

00:33:51.319 --> 00:33:54.680
Like if I put in book and look at its neighbors,

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:59.000
I see for old, I see things like poem and manuscript.

00:33:59.079 --> 00:34:03.280
On the new side, I see like company, for instance, magic.

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:05.800
And you can start to see it's picking up

00:34:05.800 --> 00:34:08.439
on important associations, but in a way that

00:34:08.439 --> 00:34:10.080
is potentially problematic.

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:15.959
So we have this thing that's powerful.

00:34:15.959 --> 00:34:17.840
It requires a lot of analysis.

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:19.280
But let's think about how we could

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:22.560
use this idea of meaningful directions in other ways,

00:34:22.560 --> 00:34:24.800
now that we have it.

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:27.520
So one way, it turns out, is to interpret

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:29.320
what's going on inside of neural networks

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:32.040
so that they're not, in fact, black boxes.

00:34:32.040 --> 00:34:35.360
And I'd like to very quickly fly through a method called

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:40.600
TCAV, published in ICML 2018.

00:34:40.600 --> 00:34:43.199
And the idea behind this method is to take this insight

00:34:43.199 --> 00:34:45.639
that, OK, if things like word embeddings

00:34:45.639 --> 00:34:48.679
have directions that sort of correspond

00:34:48.679 --> 00:34:51.120
to things that are meaningful to humans,

00:34:51.120 --> 00:34:54.560
like capital cities to capitals, maybe

00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:56.439
there are other types of embeddings

00:34:56.439 --> 00:34:57.919
that have that same property.

00:34:57.919 --> 00:35:00.840
And we could use that to our advantage.

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:05.040
So I'll illustrate this by imagining a question you

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:06.959
might ask of an image classifier.

00:35:06.959 --> 00:35:09.520
Let's say it looks at a picture of a zebra.

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:13.320
And you wonder, why did it think that thing was a zebra?

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:15.639
So there's sort of a bad answer to this question

00:35:15.639 --> 00:35:16.840
and a good answer.

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:19.120
The bad answer is if it told you something like, oh,

00:35:19.120 --> 00:35:23.040
it was this particular pixel, or these sets of pixels.

00:35:23.959 --> 00:35:26.600
Those are not terms that a human can understand.

00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:29.479
A much better answer would be if it could say something like,

00:35:29.479 --> 00:35:33.080
oh, it was striped, and that helped.

00:35:33.080 --> 00:35:35.159
Of course, it's very hard to kind of figure out

00:35:35.159 --> 00:35:37.719
how to extract that answer.

00:35:37.719 --> 00:35:39.760
However, there is a way to do it.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:42.000
So let's follow what happens if you

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:43.879
have a neural network that is recognizing

00:35:43.879 --> 00:35:45.959
an image, like zebra.

00:35:45.959 --> 00:35:47.840
So you put in an image.

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:49.840
Let's say it's an image of a zebra.

00:35:49.840 --> 00:35:52.800
And then you put it into your neural network.

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:54.800
And what is shown here is a little cartoon

00:35:54.800 --> 00:35:58.159
of one famous network called Inception.

00:35:58.159 --> 00:36:02.360
And the idea is that in this kind of network,

00:36:02.360 --> 00:36:06.199
the image gets sort of transformed layer by layer.

00:36:06.199 --> 00:36:09.320
And you can think of each layer as performing a transformation

00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:12.439
of Euclidean space.

00:36:12.439 --> 00:36:15.439
And so if you put something like zebra through it,

00:36:15.439 --> 00:36:18.399
show it an image, in each of these layers,

00:36:18.399 --> 00:36:20.040
you can think of the state of the layers

00:36:20.040 --> 00:36:22.600
as a set of activations of the neurons.

00:36:22.600 --> 00:36:24.439
And those activations form a vector

00:36:24.439 --> 00:36:25.959
in high-dimensional space.

00:36:25.959 --> 00:36:28.360
So you can see how this starts to relate to what we were just

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:29.959
looking at.

00:36:29.959 --> 00:36:32.360
And then what's interesting is if you put a whole bunch

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:34.959
of images through, you get a bunch of points

00:36:34.959 --> 00:36:36.679
in this high-dimensional space.

00:36:36.679 --> 00:36:38.719
And you can start playing this game

00:36:38.719 --> 00:36:42.080
with meaningful directions.

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:44.360
So let's show how this works.

00:36:44.360 --> 00:36:46.520
So the idea is that let's say there's

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:49.479
a concept you're interested in, for example, stripes

00:36:49.479 --> 00:36:52.080
or the presence of stripes.

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:55.000
You don't even have to try to define to the computer

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:56.679
in language what stripes is.

00:36:56.679 --> 00:37:01.159
You could just show it a bunch of examples of striped images.

00:37:01.159 --> 00:37:03.479
And then you put those striped images

00:37:03.479 --> 00:37:05.239
through your neural network.

00:37:05.239 --> 00:37:06.280
And then as you see.

00:37:06.280 --> 00:37:09.399
And one important thing, these are not images of zebras.

00:37:09.399 --> 00:37:11.639
This is just any stripes, anywhere.

00:37:11.639 --> 00:37:14.399
We've done this literally with striped ties, and striped

00:37:14.399 --> 00:37:16.840
shirts, and abstract stripes.

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:18.080
That's a good point.

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:19.520
And then what you'll get is a kind

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:22.760
of cluster of images in this space of activations

00:37:22.760 --> 00:37:25.919
in an intermediate layer that represents stripes.

00:37:25.919 --> 00:37:28.520
And then you can also put a bunch of random other images

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:31.560
through and train a classifier to distinguish

00:37:31.560 --> 00:37:33.840
between the stripes and the non-stripes.

00:37:33.840 --> 00:37:36.360
And that gives you what's called a concept activation

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:40.399
vector, a direction in space that represents that concept.

00:37:40.399 --> 00:37:42.239
And then this is what's cool, is that you

00:37:42.239 --> 00:37:44.280
can start calculating with that.

00:37:44.280 --> 00:37:46.760
That vector is something you can, for example,

00:37:46.760 --> 00:37:48.600
take directional derivatives to understand

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:51.360
the sensitivity to this concept.

00:37:51.360 --> 00:37:52.879
So computers like it.

00:37:52.879 --> 00:37:55.320
But humans like it too, because it's

00:37:55.320 --> 00:37:57.280
a human-friendly concept of stripes

00:37:57.280 --> 00:38:00.399
that they're getting an answer in terms of.

00:38:00.399 --> 00:38:03.120
So this turns out to actually be a very useful technique

00:38:03.120 --> 00:38:03.639
in general.

00:38:03.639 --> 00:38:05.800
There's a lot more we can say.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:07.879
But what's really interesting is that you

00:38:07.879 --> 00:38:11.679
can go from just interpreting or understanding directly

00:38:11.679 --> 00:38:13.879
to control.

00:38:13.879 --> 00:38:15.959
Yeah, so imagine that.

00:38:15.959 --> 00:38:19.840
You start with this super high dimensional space.

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:23.679
And you find meaning in that space, meaning that is also

00:38:23.679 --> 00:38:25.280
meaningful to humans.

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:29.320
So what I want to show you next is an example of a project

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:33.360
where we used that for health care.

00:38:33.360 --> 00:38:35.439
So here's the scenario.

00:38:35.439 --> 00:38:37.360
We were working with pathologists

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:39.760
trying to diagnose cancer.

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:42.040
And the way they work is they will

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:45.399
look at a slide of a patient, very much

00:38:45.399 --> 00:38:48.000
like the large image you see here.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.879
And then they will very, very closely analyze this image

00:38:51.879 --> 00:38:56.280
and try to understand, one, do I believe is there cancer here?

00:38:56.280 --> 00:38:59.560
And if so, what grade of cancer?

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:05.639
This is what's called Gleason 1, Gleason 2, Gleason 4, OK?

00:39:05.639 --> 00:39:09.800
And so even though there is an extensive set of work that

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:15.879
has been done with optimizing algorithmic performance

00:39:15.879 --> 00:39:19.520
to try to look at an image like this and say, yes,

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:22.040
there is cancer, no, there is no cancer,

00:39:22.040 --> 00:39:26.840
much less attention had been paid to actually what

00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:29.360
kind of information and what kind of interactions

00:39:29.360 --> 00:39:34.580
would doctors like to get out from a dialogue

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:36.280
with these systems?

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:39.719
Instead of just being given a number and a probability,

00:39:39.719 --> 00:39:43.199
do they actually want to interact and direct

00:39:43.199 --> 00:39:44.520
these systems?

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:47.679
It turns out that, yes, they would like to do this.

00:39:47.679 --> 00:39:51.600
And part of the reason why they want to do stuff like this

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:56.159
is because many times for things like sometimes

00:39:56.159 --> 00:39:58.120
there are artifacts in these images

00:39:58.120 --> 00:39:59.760
and they want to say, dismiss that.

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:01.719
I don't want you to pay attention to that thing.

00:40:01.719 --> 00:40:03.479
That's not important.

00:40:03.479 --> 00:40:09.320
Or there are anatomical features that they care deeply about,

00:40:09.399 --> 00:40:14.399
things like the density of glands or whatever other concept.

00:40:14.800 --> 00:40:15.840
And think about it.

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:17.659
Those are high level concepts, right?

00:40:17.659 --> 00:40:19.959
How do you tell the machine what I really care about

00:40:19.959 --> 00:40:23.399
or how dense the glands are here?

00:40:23.399 --> 00:40:26.360
So you can do things that have been done.

00:40:26.360 --> 00:40:28.639
We're going to talk about this.

00:40:28.639 --> 00:40:33.520
But basically what we did is we created a set of tools

00:40:33.520 --> 00:40:37.239
that allowed pathologists to very quickly navigate

00:40:37.239 --> 00:40:40.120
these highly massive data sets.

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:41.600
Because again, what they're trying to do,

00:40:41.600 --> 00:40:42.840
they're looking at that slide

00:40:42.840 --> 00:40:45.679
and they are trying to get the system

00:40:45.679 --> 00:40:49.600
to bring to them the nearest neighbors, right?

00:40:49.600 --> 00:40:53.699
What is the patient I've seen before that has been diagnosed?

00:40:54.800 --> 00:40:58.320
What is the closest case to this case I'm seeing now?

00:40:59.459 --> 00:41:01.020
But that's not a one-shot thing.

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:02.320
That is the thing that's interesting.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:04.219
It's not just like automate that.

00:41:04.219 --> 00:41:07.179
So one of the things is just allowing people

00:41:07.179 --> 00:41:09.780
to cut little, to say, focus here.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:11.679
That's what I want to do.

00:41:11.679 --> 00:41:14.500
Things like these have been done before, right?

00:41:14.500 --> 00:41:18.219
Or once you bring me a bunch of cases

00:41:18.219 --> 00:41:21.360
that are like the case I just highlighted for you,

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:25.159
now let me go deeper into one of those cases

00:41:25.159 --> 00:41:29.659
and bring me more closest neighbors to those cases.

00:41:29.659 --> 00:41:33.739
So in other words, let me navigate by example.

00:41:33.780 --> 00:41:35.520
I want you to pay attention to this now.

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:36.540
Now let me go back.

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:38.780
I want you to pay attention to, oh, this is interesting.

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:40.060
Let's go that way.

00:41:40.899 --> 00:41:44.659
Okay, all of that kind of had been done before.

00:41:45.639 --> 00:41:48.580
The thing that's new that we can do

00:41:48.580 --> 00:41:53.580
is now with things like CAVs that you just heard about,

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:58.540
we can actually create much more sophisticated ways

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:02.219
of navigating these systems in medical concepts.

00:42:02.219 --> 00:42:04.659
So working with the pathologists,

00:42:04.659 --> 00:42:09.060
they told us that a medical concept they deeply care about

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:10.979
is something called stroma.

00:42:10.979 --> 00:42:11.939
I'm not a doctor.

00:42:11.939 --> 00:42:13.520
I had no idea what this was,

00:42:13.520 --> 00:42:15.979
but for them, it was super interesting.

00:42:15.979 --> 00:42:18.580
So we created a slider where they could say,

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:22.500
show me cases like this, but with more stroma

00:42:22.500 --> 00:42:26.179
or with less stroma or fused glands.

00:42:26.179 --> 00:42:29.459
That's another medical concept they care deeply about.

00:42:29.459 --> 00:42:34.459
And so because again, these ML systems

00:42:35.459 --> 00:42:38.580
inside these highly massive spaces,

00:42:38.580 --> 00:42:40.580
there are meaningful directions.

00:42:40.580 --> 00:42:43.959
We were able to map these medical concepts

00:42:43.959 --> 00:42:48.959
to these meaningful directions in the system.

00:42:49.379 --> 00:42:53.379
And that gave doctors a much more powerful way

00:42:53.379 --> 00:42:55.260
of interacting with the systems.

00:42:55.260 --> 00:42:58.580
And one of the really important things here

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:02.300
is to actually for the doctor to calibrate their trust.

00:43:02.300 --> 00:43:03.739
Should I trust this?

00:43:03.739 --> 00:43:05.260
Should I not trust this?

00:43:05.260 --> 00:43:08.120
Or even to learn how the system works.

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:09.260
How does it behave?

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:11.620
How does it think about edge cases?

00:43:11.620 --> 00:43:13.760
And so we actually had a user study.

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:18.320
In this case was with 12 pathologists

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:21.780
looking both at a traditional machine learning system

00:43:21.780 --> 00:43:25.979
that just gives you a prediction with a confidence level,

00:43:25.979 --> 00:43:28.340
or this system called Smiley,

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:30.219
where you have all these different tools

00:43:30.219 --> 00:43:32.739
that you can interact with.

00:43:32.739 --> 00:43:35.139
And the results were very positive.

00:43:35.139 --> 00:43:40.139
Basically, all 12 pathologists preferred Smiley.

00:43:42.820 --> 00:43:47.820
The level of trust was significantly higher.

00:43:50.179 --> 00:43:52.580
And even though you would think,

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:57.020
if you could only automate my work for me, I'd be done.

00:43:57.020 --> 00:44:02.020
They actually found a lot of use in going back and forth.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:06.540
But not only that, steering the system

00:44:06.540 --> 00:44:08.500
in ways that they cared about.

00:44:12.580 --> 00:44:17.300
Okay, so yeah, I think what you see from this

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:20.340
is sort of the ability of statistical analysis

00:44:20.340 --> 00:44:22.100
to actually help steer these systems.

00:44:22.699 --> 00:44:24.899
I want to talk about another aspect of this.

00:44:25.820 --> 00:44:26.699
So here I'm going to ask you

00:44:26.699 --> 00:44:28.899
to actually do some imagining here,

00:44:28.899 --> 00:44:31.060
and even answer some questions in your head.

00:44:31.060 --> 00:44:34.459
So situation is, imagine you're a company,

00:44:34.459 --> 00:44:36.580
or non-profit, whatever.

00:44:36.580 --> 00:44:38.020
You're designing a system

00:44:38.020 --> 00:44:40.899
to recommend books to library patrons.

00:44:40.899 --> 00:44:43.919
And let's imagine you have a team of people doing this.

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:48.479
And you have engineers,

00:44:48.479 --> 00:44:51.100
maybe you have someone who is responsible for the design,

00:44:51.139 --> 00:44:53.419
and I mean that broadly in terms of user experience,

00:44:53.419 --> 00:44:55.699
or UX, as people say.

00:44:55.699 --> 00:44:58.139
And you're going over a bunch of the big decisions

00:44:58.139 --> 00:45:00.300
and small decisions that you'll have to make.

00:45:00.300 --> 00:45:02.699
And which ones do you need to consult

00:45:02.699 --> 00:45:05.500
that user experience designer on?

00:45:05.500 --> 00:45:07.739
And so let's just go through some questions,

00:45:07.739 --> 00:45:10.139
and you can think about this.

00:45:11.379 --> 00:45:14.300
Does the system show one recommendation or many?

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:16.060
What hardware does it run on?

00:45:16.060 --> 00:45:18.179
Just answer these in your head.

00:45:18.260 --> 00:45:21.540
Do users see an explanation for recommendations?

00:45:21.540 --> 00:45:24.620
Which database to store your metadata in?

00:45:24.620 --> 00:45:26.459
When should you bother that designer?

00:45:26.459 --> 00:45:29.139
What typeface do we use for recommendations?

00:45:29.139 --> 00:45:31.100
Do we use this particular loss function,

00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:34.500
which I will not read out loud, it's tech.

00:45:35.419 --> 00:45:38.179
Do we allow users to like a recommendation?

00:45:38.179 --> 00:45:42.659
And should our L2 regularization constant be 9.83?

00:45:42.659 --> 00:45:45.820
Okay, so you might have some answers in mind.

00:45:45.820 --> 00:45:48.860
Some, I think, are actually kind of obvious.

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:50.459
Clearly, you should talk to your designer

00:45:50.459 --> 00:45:52.780
about whether you show one recommendation or many.

00:45:52.780 --> 00:45:54.379
They should be involved in that.

00:45:55.379 --> 00:45:58.419
I think some are not really design issues,

00:45:58.419 --> 00:46:02.100
like what database you use to store metadata.

00:46:02.100 --> 00:46:03.139
Their time is precious.

00:46:03.139 --> 00:46:05.219
They don't need to weigh in on that.

00:46:05.219 --> 00:46:08.340
However, there is one weird question here,

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:10.500
which is the loss function.

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:13.260
And we would argue that in many cases,

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:17.139
this may be the most important UX decision of all.

00:46:18.979 --> 00:46:21.419
And which seems very counterintuitive.

00:46:21.419 --> 00:46:24.659
Why would a chunk of math be a user experience issue?

00:46:25.780 --> 00:46:28.860
And the answer is that essentially

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:29.860
in a machine learning system,

00:46:29.860 --> 00:46:32.860
your loss function expresses the goal

00:46:32.860 --> 00:46:35.219
of what your system is doing.

00:46:36.459 --> 00:46:40.260
And that goal, ultimately exactly what happens in practice,

00:46:40.260 --> 00:46:42.100
that tells you whether people are more likely

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.899
to see bad recommendations or good ones,

00:46:44.899 --> 00:46:46.580
are they going to see similar ones,

00:46:46.580 --> 00:46:48.100
or diverse and more diverse ones,

00:46:48.100 --> 00:46:50.580
and many, many other aspects.

00:46:50.580 --> 00:46:54.459
We see this anywhere recommendation systems are used.

00:46:54.459 --> 00:46:58.219
And again, kind of a sobering thought,

00:46:58.219 --> 00:47:00.379
because how do you understand this thing?

00:47:00.379 --> 00:47:02.300
Like, can a mathematician just stare at it

00:47:02.300 --> 00:47:03.459
and figure out the effects?

00:47:03.459 --> 00:47:04.780
No.

00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:08.540
But a statistician, you've got a good chance

00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:11.939
if you look at pilot tests, use in practice,

00:47:12.780 --> 00:47:14.379
run simulations, you've got a whole bunch of tools

00:47:14.379 --> 00:47:15.580
to look at.

00:47:15.580 --> 00:47:17.100
And so what this says, I think,

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:20.379
in the new world that we find ourselves in with AI,

00:47:20.379 --> 00:47:23.979
is that statisticians, or anyone who works with data,

00:47:23.979 --> 00:47:26.300
has an incredibly important role to play.

00:47:27.540 --> 00:47:31.020
The models that you create are having broad effects

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:32.139
on all sorts of people.

00:47:32.139 --> 00:47:34.459
As you think about what stakeholders,

00:47:34.459 --> 00:47:36.219
who you want to take care of,

00:47:36.219 --> 00:47:37.939
think about also who you want to talk to.

00:47:37.939 --> 00:47:41.300
Like, as you're writing a formula for your loss function,

00:47:41.300 --> 00:47:43.379
maybe you should talk to a UX designer.

00:47:43.379 --> 00:47:45.979
As you do that, get their opinion.

00:47:45.979 --> 00:47:48.419
That could be as good a moment for a user test

00:47:48.419 --> 00:47:50.500
or ethnography as any other moment

00:47:50.500 --> 00:47:52.340
in the design of the system.

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:53.620
You have a lot of power.

00:47:55.620 --> 00:47:58.860
And so, even though traditionally design

00:47:58.860 --> 00:48:01.300
may have looked like this, right,

00:48:01.300 --> 00:48:04.860
with the colors and the values,

00:48:05.699 --> 00:48:09.659
we believe that in the current era of machine learning,

00:48:09.659 --> 00:48:12.899
design is both of these things.

00:48:12.899 --> 00:48:13.979
It needs to be.

00:48:13.979 --> 00:48:16.540
We need to start thinking that way, we believe.

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:23.060
And so, basically, our thought to leave you with today

00:48:23.379 --> 00:48:28.060
is that if you work in R, or with data, or with ML code,

00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:30.979
you are part of the user experience team,

00:48:30.979 --> 00:48:32.899
whether or not you know it.

00:48:32.899 --> 00:48:36.419
And you have a lot of power, as Martin was saying.

00:48:36.419 --> 00:48:37.419
So think about that.

00:48:37.419 --> 00:48:41.620
Think about how you're going to bridge

00:48:41.620 --> 00:48:46.219
between the world of data and what you see in the models,

00:48:46.219 --> 00:48:51.219
in the data logs you see, in the data analysis you make,

00:48:51.219 --> 00:48:54.699
and what the end user experience is going to be,

00:48:54.699 --> 00:48:59.340
because it's going to depend more and more on this bridge.

00:48:59.340 --> 00:49:03.139
And so, just to leave you with one resource,

00:49:03.139 --> 00:49:05.580
hopefully, that could be helpful.

00:49:06.580 --> 00:49:11.580
This guidebook is something Pear launched last May,

00:49:13.100 --> 00:49:18.100
and it's a set of guidelines that tries to be very concrete

00:49:20.780 --> 00:49:23.139
about what does it mean to build

00:49:23.139 --> 00:49:26.379
and ship AI-enabled products.

00:49:26.379 --> 00:49:30.340
This is something that took over 150 Googlers

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:34.219
from all over the company to come together.

00:49:34.219 --> 00:49:37.899
We also had academics that we consulted with.

00:49:37.899 --> 00:49:40.139
This was very much, this came from

00:49:40.139 --> 00:49:42.580
a lot of our internal experience

00:49:42.580 --> 00:49:44.899
shipping AI-enabled products.

00:49:46.459 --> 00:49:50.060
But this is something that needs to go,

00:49:50.060 --> 00:49:52.620
needs to be much, much bigger than Google.

00:49:52.620 --> 00:49:56.379
This is just the beginning of trying to go

00:49:56.379 --> 00:49:58.419
from those very lofty goals,

00:49:58.419 --> 00:50:01.179
like we need to make machine learning fair,

00:50:01.179 --> 00:50:04.139
we need to make machine learning explainable,

00:50:04.939 --> 00:50:07.419
to the, okay, how do we get there?

00:50:07.419 --> 00:50:10.500
How do we do this when I have to ship a product

00:50:10.500 --> 00:50:13.379
in the next three weeks?

00:50:13.379 --> 00:50:17.340
So this is a quick view of the different chapters

00:50:18.260 --> 00:50:20.540
that the guidebook has.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:23.540
It's full of samples,

00:50:24.979 --> 00:50:28.100
do's and don'ts on the user experience side,

00:50:28.100 --> 00:50:30.100
step-by-step guidelines,

00:50:30.100 --> 00:50:32.540
and also interactive worksheets.

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:35.379
And the whole point is that this is going to take

00:50:35.379 --> 00:50:37.739
an entire team to figure out.

00:50:37.739 --> 00:50:40.979
This is not just the UXers or the engineers

00:50:40.979 --> 00:50:43.100
or the data scientists.

00:50:43.100 --> 00:50:46.060
We're gonna have to be talking, all of us together,

00:50:46.060 --> 00:50:50.459
and you all hold a lot of power in that conversation.

00:50:51.340 --> 00:50:52.659
So that's it.

00:50:52.659 --> 00:50:53.739
Thank you so much.

00:50:54.379 --> 00:50:55.219
Thank you.

00:51:07.340 --> 00:51:10.179
So I'm gonna add a little editorial voice.

00:51:11.500 --> 00:51:13.020
Anonymous asks,

00:51:13.020 --> 00:51:17.260
why are you, as visualization experts, using pie charts?

00:51:19.179 --> 00:51:22.300
Don't get me started on pie charts.

00:51:22.340 --> 00:51:24.860
I think they are so underrated.

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:28.179
I actually think there are many, many good aspects

00:51:28.179 --> 00:51:29.060
of pie charts.

00:51:30.780 --> 00:51:34.020
In cases where you have only a few items,

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:35.379
like three or four,

00:51:35.379 --> 00:51:38.379
and where you're interested in the sizes of sums

00:51:38.379 --> 00:51:40.659
of wedges that are next to each other,

00:51:40.659 --> 00:51:43.899
I actually think they have many advantages over bar charts.

00:51:43.899 --> 00:51:45.500
There are certain queries you can make,

00:51:45.500 --> 00:51:48.060
like is there anything that has a majority,

00:51:48.060 --> 00:51:50.780
or are there two slices that have a majority

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:53.899
compared to a third, or two others?

00:51:53.899 --> 00:51:55.580
They're much easier.

00:51:55.580 --> 00:51:58.459
If you look at the history of research into pie charts,

00:51:58.459 --> 00:52:02.139
people have been trying, literally since the 1920s,

00:52:02.139 --> 00:52:03.459
to prove that they're bad,

00:52:03.459 --> 00:52:05.300
and they never really have.

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:06.899
So, anyway.

00:52:06.899 --> 00:52:08.219
Don't get me started.

00:52:08.219 --> 00:52:09.060
Oops.

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:16.419
So we have quite a few questions,

00:52:16.419 --> 00:52:18.780
just about what tools did you use

00:52:18.780 --> 00:52:20.939
to make these visualizations?

00:52:20.939 --> 00:52:25.179
Oh, so most of the things you saw today

00:52:25.179 --> 00:52:28.060
are JavaScript tools.

00:52:28.060 --> 00:52:32.060
And we tend to code things from scratch.

00:52:35.379 --> 00:52:36.459
It's a...

00:52:36.459 --> 00:52:38.540
I mean, D3 is very helpful.

00:52:38.540 --> 00:52:42.540
I also think that WebGL has been sort of amazing.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:45.340
That's been a huge technical advance.

00:52:45.340 --> 00:52:48.659
Like that, when I think about what has changed

00:52:49.540 --> 00:52:50.979
since when I first started doing visualization,

00:52:50.979 --> 00:52:52.459
there are things you can do,

00:52:52.459 --> 00:52:55.459
just the number of images you can animate

00:52:55.459 --> 00:52:58.580
at one time smoothly, that's been a big deal.

00:52:58.580 --> 00:53:00.699
One thing that I think we forgot to say,

00:53:00.699 --> 00:53:04.219
the embedding projector that you saw Martin demo today,

00:53:04.219 --> 00:53:06.899
that's also open source, that's also available,

00:53:06.899 --> 00:53:09.340
and anyone can play with it.

00:53:09.340 --> 00:53:10.739
So I had a personal question,

00:53:10.739 --> 00:53:12.219
which is it looked like one of those plots

00:53:12.219 --> 00:53:16.260
was a ggplot2 plot, is that correct?

00:53:16.260 --> 00:53:20.260
It probably is, actually, yes.

00:53:23.620 --> 00:53:25.939
Taylor asks, facets is a beautiful tool

00:53:25.939 --> 00:53:27.620
for exploring image data,

00:53:27.620 --> 00:53:30.939
what strategies do you use when you've got non-image data,

00:53:30.939 --> 00:53:34.939
like 400 variables trying to predict a class?

00:53:36.500 --> 00:53:39.379
So it depends on the type of variable.

00:53:39.379 --> 00:53:43.379
So we certainly do a bunch of things.

00:53:43.379 --> 00:53:45.060
And the idea of slicing and dicing,

00:53:45.139 --> 00:53:48.060
you usually have to pick a couple of variables to focus on.

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:50.300
There are a couple of things.

00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:52.820
So one is, in many cases,

00:53:52.820 --> 00:53:55.820
you can actually use something like the embedding projector,

00:53:55.820 --> 00:53:59.540
depending on the type of variables, to do clustering.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:02.179
In other cases, I don't know that we have

00:54:02.179 --> 00:54:04.020
a really good solution to offer.

00:54:04.020 --> 00:54:07.540
And again, this is exactly why I think

00:54:07.540 --> 00:54:09.939
you, the audience, have power,

00:54:09.939 --> 00:54:12.860
is that there's a wide opening for you

00:54:12.860 --> 00:54:14.379
to actually make a big difference

00:54:14.379 --> 00:54:16.300
in this field by providing good tools.

00:54:21.100 --> 00:54:22.580
So Yim Register asks,

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:25.419
literacy is awesome for developers,

00:54:25.419 --> 00:54:27.500
but are you also thinking about pathways

00:54:27.500 --> 00:54:30.020
for people affected by these models,

00:54:30.020 --> 00:54:33.459
so they can self-advocate about models that exclude them?

00:54:34.500 --> 00:54:37.780
Yeah, so one of the things that we're working on,

00:54:37.780 --> 00:54:40.939
that's a very good question, I think it's a very hard one.

00:54:40.939 --> 00:54:43.500
One of the things we're working on

00:54:43.500 --> 00:54:48.500
is just AI literacy in general.

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:52.260
So we are developing a number of educational materials.

00:54:52.260 --> 00:54:54.939
The visualization you saw with fairness

00:54:54.939 --> 00:54:58.300
was one of these moments when we realized,

00:54:58.300 --> 00:55:00.020
oh, these simple visualizations

00:55:00.020 --> 00:55:01.899
actually have a lot of power.

00:55:01.899 --> 00:55:05.620
Just to exactly that, start to educate people.

00:55:05.620 --> 00:55:10.620
We want way, a much broader set of folks to be critical

00:55:11.260 --> 00:55:14.739
and to be engaged at a certain level with this,

00:55:14.739 --> 00:55:17.260
at a level where they feel they know

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:20.340
what questions to ask of the technology.

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:23.620
And so all of the stuff that we work on,

00:55:23.620 --> 00:55:28.260
we try to make it open source, make it available publicly.

00:55:28.260 --> 00:55:33.260
But I also think that creating tools that are code-free

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:38.620
is extremely important, exactly to lower the barrier

00:55:38.659 --> 00:55:40.659
and to start to bridge the communities.

00:55:42.020 --> 00:55:42.899
Awesome.

00:55:42.899 --> 00:55:44.899
We also had a few questions,

00:55:44.899 --> 00:55:47.139
like you are embedded inside Google,

00:55:47.139 --> 00:55:49.620
which clearly uses a bunch of algorithms

00:55:49.620 --> 00:55:51.020
and sometimes those algorithms are good

00:55:51.020 --> 00:55:52.620
and sometimes they're bad.

00:55:52.620 --> 00:55:55.179
How do you see your role in shifting

00:55:55.179 --> 00:55:58.379
how Google uses algorithms for good?

00:55:58.379 --> 00:55:59.739
We like good algorithms.

00:56:00.739 --> 00:56:03.979
And I think more importantly, I think in general,

00:56:03.979 --> 00:56:05.939
people want to do the right thing.

00:56:05.939 --> 00:56:08.459
And I think one of the things that's important

00:56:09.300 --> 00:56:13.340
is to give people tools to make it sort of understandable

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:14.500
what to do.

00:56:14.500 --> 00:56:17.179
One of the things that is important,

00:56:17.179 --> 00:56:20.580
like it can be very hard to know,

00:56:20.580 --> 00:56:23.139
like these things are very complicated systems

00:56:23.139 --> 00:56:27.899
and the more tools that we have to help us figure out,

00:56:27.899 --> 00:56:30.500
okay, let's do this rather than do that,

00:56:30.500 --> 00:56:33.100
how do we make decisions around them, the better.

00:56:33.100 --> 00:56:35.419
So we definitely view ourselves as making tools

00:56:35.419 --> 00:56:38.419
both for Google and as we open source them, we want.

00:56:39.260 --> 00:56:40.620
I think it's for the whole world as well.

00:56:40.620 --> 00:56:41.659
Awesome, thank you.

00:56:41.659 --> 00:56:43.699
I had another personal question,

00:56:43.699 --> 00:56:45.979
which is how long do you spend coming up

00:56:45.979 --> 00:56:49.340
with like humorous and good acronyms for your products?

00:56:49.340 --> 00:56:50.179
Ah!

00:56:50.179 --> 00:56:53.100
No, I didn't know.

00:56:53.100 --> 00:56:56.020
Yeah, you need to do more of that.

00:56:59.939 --> 00:57:04.939
Let's see, what else do we have?

00:57:05.939 --> 00:57:09.580
Have you created any examples to illustrate the intuition

00:57:09.580 --> 00:57:11.699
behind adversarial images?

00:57:12.780 --> 00:57:16.379
Yeah, so between adversarial images?

00:57:16.379 --> 00:57:19.219
Oh, okay, so no.

00:57:20.260 --> 00:57:22.020
For a moment I thought you said generative

00:57:22.020 --> 00:57:24.139
adversarial networks, and we do have one of those,

00:57:24.139 --> 00:57:25.500
something called GAN Lab.

00:57:25.500 --> 00:57:30.500
But adversarial images are super interesting and weird.

00:57:30.500 --> 00:57:33.100
Just for those who may not have heard of them,

00:57:33.100 --> 00:57:35.899
it's this phenomenon that you can take an image

00:57:35.899 --> 00:57:38.540
that a computer is correctly certain about,

00:57:38.540 --> 00:57:41.459
like it's a picture of a cat, it's not a frog or something.

00:57:41.459 --> 00:57:43.419
It for sure sees it as a cat.

00:57:43.419 --> 00:57:46.540
You change the pixels in a tiny amount

00:57:46.540 --> 00:57:48.820
so that it's imperceptible to a human,

00:57:48.820 --> 00:57:50.820
and all of a sudden the computer is certain

00:57:50.820 --> 00:57:53.179
it's like a bathtub or something.

00:57:53.179 --> 00:57:56.100
And at first it was seen as like some sort

00:57:56.100 --> 00:57:59.100
of weird one-off bug, but what's been clear

00:57:59.100 --> 00:58:00.699
is that it's like a pervasive thing

00:58:00.699 --> 00:58:03.540
that happens across lots of classifiers.

00:58:03.540 --> 00:58:05.860
I think one of the reasons I don't think

00:58:05.860 --> 00:58:08.219
we've created something that sort of helps people

00:58:08.219 --> 00:58:11.139
understand it is that the research community itself,

00:58:12.100 --> 00:58:14.580
I don't think there's a crisp explanation.

00:58:14.580 --> 00:58:16.739
It's one of the genuine mysteries.

00:58:16.739 --> 00:58:19.459
There's some interesting ideas about maybe this has to do

00:58:19.459 --> 00:58:21.340
with the high dimensional nature of the data,

00:58:21.340 --> 00:58:24.219
and any imperfect classifier might have these,

00:58:24.219 --> 00:58:27.500
or that in fact there are important things

00:58:27.500 --> 00:58:29.979
that a computer picks up on in terms of texture

00:58:29.979 --> 00:58:31.820
that the human eye is just bad at.

00:58:32.860 --> 00:58:35.300
But I don't know that there's a final answer to that.

00:58:35.300 --> 00:58:36.540
Therefore it's very hard to make

00:58:36.540 --> 00:58:38.620
an easy, crisp visualization of it.

00:58:38.620 --> 00:58:39.939
But it's a great question, actually.

00:58:39.939 --> 00:58:42.139
It's something probably we should try.

00:58:42.139 --> 00:58:42.979
Thanks.

00:58:42.979 --> 00:58:44.459
I think we'll do one last question.

00:58:44.459 --> 00:58:45.939
So you've showed a bunch of tools today

00:58:45.939 --> 00:58:48.500
that you can use in your browser.

00:58:48.500 --> 00:58:50.260
Does the data ever go to Google's server,

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:52.419
or can you use it with like confidential data,

00:58:52.419 --> 00:58:54.179
like HIPAA protected data, or?

00:58:55.100 --> 00:58:58.300
So anything that's available on the cloud,

00:58:58.300 --> 00:59:00.300
on Google Cloud, you should be able to use

00:59:00.300 --> 00:59:03.820
with your own data and confidentiality for sure.

00:59:05.379 --> 00:59:07.659
I mean, there is a question about device,

00:59:07.659 --> 00:59:09.419
on device versus off device.

00:59:09.419 --> 00:59:11.300
And what I would say is,

00:59:11.300 --> 00:59:13.939
rather than giving a crisp answer to that up here,

00:59:13.939 --> 00:59:16.379
I would read carefully the fine print of whichever tool,

00:59:16.379 --> 00:59:21.379
but many of these things do in fact keep the data on device.

00:59:22.260 --> 00:59:24.139
There is a whole other project

00:59:24.139 --> 00:59:26.060
we didn't get to talk about today here,

00:59:26.060 --> 00:59:28.459
but if you are interested,

00:59:28.459 --> 00:59:32.699
tensorflow.js is, it brings machine learning

00:59:32.699 --> 00:59:33.939
to your browser.

00:59:33.939 --> 00:59:37.419
And one of the perks of that,

00:59:37.419 --> 00:59:39.300
there's no install, there's no download,

00:59:39.300 --> 00:59:42.100
but one of the biggest perks is privacy,

00:59:42.100 --> 00:59:44.979
because it runs all locally.

00:59:44.979 --> 00:59:47.620
Nothing gets sent to any server.

00:59:47.620 --> 00:59:50.979
And so this is, we didn't have time to talk about it today,

00:59:50.979 --> 00:59:53.739
but it's definitely worth checking out.

00:59:54.780 --> 00:59:55.620
Awesome.

00:59:55.939 --> 00:59:57.939
So please join me in thanking Fernanda and Martin.

00:59:57.939 --> 00:59:58.899
Thank you.

00:59:58.899 --> 00:59:59.939
Thank you.

00:59:59.939 --> 01:00:01.419
Thank you, Martín.

